reviews.review: Once again we see the so called art critics and the audience disagree. The film was amazing, and would have been far better only if JJ Abrams didn't have to repair all the disasters that the Last Jedi created (thanks Rian Johnson). Meanwhile critics will find a way to dislike it, and ignore the epic conclusion to a Shakespearean tale of Space Opera created by George Lucas over 40 years ago.
Yeah baby yeah Rey and pow

To my surprise... I really enjoyed it. A major course correction from the abomination of the subversive and nihilistic, The Last Jedi. With Rise of Skywalker I laughed a lot, cried some, and cheered with the audience! It had the soul of a Star Wars movie with the themes focused on family, friendship, faith, and redemption.

The Rise of Skywalker was a very frenetic movie, a departure from what one expects a usual Star Wars movie to be.

The first thing I noticed was that the score didn't stand out. There was a lot of repetition, and no theme that hadn't already appeared somewhere in the Star Wars cinematic universe stood out. 

The reveals in the movie seemed to exist solely for the purpose of a "gotcha" moment. While the concepts were interesting (and honestly could have been better explored for a more fulfilling movie), the rest of it raced by, almost as if they didn't want the viewer to stop and think about how many plot holes there were. Entertaining, but ultimately disappointing.
Underwhelming. Spectacle was great. Plot was confusing. Ending was lacking.
Loved it. Find the reviews stating it walked back Last Jedi amusing in that the reviewers thought it had a plot.

Love it or hate it... the 360+ people that took the time to review the "Rise of Skywalker" (at the time I write this) and more so took the time to go see it, proved it was a success for Disney, just as the Mandalorian series is and also the soon to arrive, baby Yoda, to a store near you will be. I liked the "Rise of Skywalker", I keep things into prospective and enjoy it for what it is: a very well done tale, first told George Lucas and now by Disney. Wouldn't you wish you were a fraction of how successful they have been? Just enjoy it for what it is... I saw the original one, chapter IV, when I was 12 and still enjoy them!
one ring to rule them all
